class="expand-img-horiz" itemprop="url" src="http://www.gannett-cdn.com/-mm-/6e692618ead22efd1bb5f481476a66d82c39266a/c=58-0-966-683&amp;r=x404&amp;c=534x401/local/-/media/2016/02/14/USATODAY/USATODAY/635910527979945171-corn3.JPG" alt="635910527979945171-corn3.JPG" data-mycapture-src="http://www.gannett-cdn.com/media/2016/02/14/USATODAY/USATODAY/635910527979945171-corn3.JPG" data-mycapture-sm-src="http://www.gannett-cdn.com/-mm-/4044b1e7645488621f157de466cf1a990870caa2/r=500x333/local/-/media/2016/02/14/USATODAY/USATODAY/635910527979945171-corn3.JPG" /><span class="toggle"></span><meta itemprop="name" content="635910527979945171-corn3.JPG" /></div><p class="image-credit-wrap"><span class="js-caption-wrapper"><span class="cutline js-caption">The Republican presidential debate in Greenville, S.C., on Feb. 13, 2016.</span><meta itemprop="copyrightHolder" content="" /><span class="credit">(Photo: Erik S. Lesser, epa)</span></span></p></aside></section></div></div><div id="module-position-O4iZ75U3OuU" class="story-asset inline-share-tools-asset"><div class="inline-share-tools asset-inline-share-tools asset-inline-share-tools-top"><span\n        class="inline-share-btn inline-share-btn-facebook"\n        data-share-method="facebook"\n        data-uotrack="InlineShareFacebookBtn"><span class="inline-share-count inline-share-count-facebook">\n            \n                728\n            \n        </span><span class="inline-share-btn-label inline-share-btn-label-facebook">CONNECT</span></span><a\n        class="inline-share-btn inline-share-btn-twitter"\n        data-share-method="twitter"\n        data-uotrack="InlineShareTwitterLink"\n        data-popup-width="550"\n        data-popup-height="450"\n        href="https://twitter.com/intent/tweet?url=http%3A//usat.ly/1XsLygo&amp;text=Court%20fight%20signals%20ugly%20end%20to%20Obama%20era%3A%20David%20Corn&amp;via=usatoday"\n        target="_blank" data-popup><span class="inline-share-count inline-share-count-twitter"></span><span class="inline-share-btn-label inline-share-btn-label-twitter">TWEET</span></a><a \n        class="inline-share-btn inline-share-btn-linkedin"\n        data-share-method="linkedin"\n        data-popup-width="600"\n        data-popup-height="455"\n        data-uotrack="UtilityBarFlyoutLinkedInLink"\n        href="http://www.linkedin.com/shareArticle?url=http%3A//usat.ly/1XsLygo&amp;mini=true"\n        target="_blank" data-popup\n                ><span class="inline-share-count inline-share-count-linkedin">\n            \n                1\n            \n        </span><span class="inline-share-btn-label inline-share-btn-label-linkedin">LINKEDIN</span></a><span\n            class="inline-share-btn inline-share-btn-comments"\n            data-share-method="comments"\n            data-uotrack="InlineShareCommentsBtn"><span class="inline-share-count inline-share-count-comments">\n                \n                    105\n                \n            </span><span class="inline-share-btn-label inline-share-btn-label-comments">COMMENT</span></span><span\n        class="inline-share-btn inline-share-btn-email"\n        data-share-method="email"\n        data-uotrack="InlineShareEmailBtn"><span class="inline-share-count inline-share-count-email"></span><span class="inline-share-btn-label inline-share-btn-label-email">EMAIL</span></span><span\n         class="inline-share-btn inline-share-btn-more"\n         data-share-method="facebook"\n         data-uotrack="InlineShareMoreBtn"><span class="inline-share-count inline-share-count-more"></span><span class="inline-share-btn-label inline-share-btn-label-more">MORE</span></span></div></div><p>Within moments of the announcement that Supreme Court Justice Antonin Scalia had died, Republicans and conservatives signaled they intended to end the Obama years exactly as they had begun them: with partisan- and ideologically-fueled obstructionism. Before the nation had time to ponder Scalia\xe2\x80\x99s impact on American jurisprudence and society, prominent conservatives and GOP presidential candidates were vowing, through tweets, to block President Barack Obama from filling the vacancy on the Supreme Court.\xc2\xa0This could well be the Republicans\xe2\x80\x99\xc2\xa0final battle in the war on Obama.</p><p>That war began the night of his inauguration. As noted political journalist <a href="http://www.huffingtonpost.com/2012/04/25/robert-draper-anti-obama-campaign_n_1452899.html">Robert Draper has reported</a>,\xc2\xa0that evening top Republican lawmakers and strategists gathered in Washington and plotted how to torpedo Obama\xe2\x80\x99s presidency from the get-go. And years of conflict followed, as GOPers refused to support Obama\xe2\x80\x99s stimulus (which created or saved millions of jobs, according to the <a href="https://www.cbo.gov/publication/45122">Congressional Budget Office</a>), demonized Obamacare (death panels!), opposed the successful auto industry bailout, blocked immigration reform, caused a government shutdown, nearly triggered a national default, played footsie with birthers\xc2\xa0and accused the president of being either weak and feckless or dictatorial and conniving.</p><p>This fight over the Scalia successor is the latest effort on the right to delegitimize Obama, who did win two national presidential elections <a href="http://www.bloomberg.com/news/articles/2013-01-03/final-tally-shows-obama-first-since-56-to-win-51-twice">by significant margins</a>.</p><p>As soon as the news of Scalia\xe2\x80\x99s death hit the Internet, Sen. Ted Cruz, who\xe2\x80\x99s locked in a tough presidential primary contest, <a href="/story/news/politics/onpolitics/2016/02/13/antonin-scalia-ted-cruz-donald-trump-john-kasich-jeb-bush/80350972/\'">declared</a> that the Republican-controlled Senate should not accept any Obama nominee. Sen. Marco Rubio, looking to not be outflanked on his right, quickly echoed Cruz\xe2\x80\x99s call. Here was a cheap and easy way for GOP presidential wannabes to toss out\xc2\xa0one large chunk of red meat to the Obama-detesting base of their party. <a href="http://www.politico.com/story/2016/02/mitch-mcconnell-antonin-scalia-supreme-court-nomination-219248">Within minutes</a>, Sen. Mitch McConnell, the Senate majority leader, was on the no-justice-for-Obama bandwagon.</p><p>There is no substantive reason to deny the president this appointment. His second term does not end at three years and three weeks. At the debate in South Carolina on Saturday night, Cruz said that it was wrong to confirm a justice during an election year. But Democratic senators joined Republicans in <a href="http://www.nytimes.com/1988/02/04/us/senate-97-to-0-confirms-kennedy-to-high-court.html">February 1988</a> to confirm Justice Anthony Kennedy, who was nominated by President Ronald Reagan. And as the office of Sen.\xc2\xa0Harry Reid, the top Democrat in the Senate, pointed out this weekend, the <a href="http://thehill.com/blogs/floor-action/senate/269393-reid-obama-should-send-supreme-court-nominee-right-away">average length of time</a> from nomination to confirmation for a justice since the Gerald Ford administration\xc2\xa0is a little over two months. So there\xe2\x80\x99s plenty of time for Obama to pick a nominee and for the Senate to do its job. By the way, how many of the Republicans running for president now would commit to <em>not</em> nominating a justice in their last year in office?</p><div id="module-position-O4iZ75UNUzA" class="story-asset oembed-asset"><div class="story-oembed-wrap "><div \n        class="js-oembed story-oembed story-oembed-usa-today story-oembed-type-link"\n        data-oembed-type="link"\n        data-oembed-provider="usa-today"><style>\n.oembed-asset-link { background: #fff; border-bottom: 1px solid #e1e1e1; }\n.oembed-link-anchor { display: block; clear: both; }\n.oembed-link-thumbnail{ float: left; padding: 14px; }\n.oembed-link-thumbnail img { max-width: 78px; max-height: 60px; display: block; }\np.oembed-link-title { font-size: 75%; color: #009BFF; margin: 0 14px; padding-top: 12px; font-weight:normal; text-align: left; line-height: 120%;  }\np.oembed-link-desc { font-size: 100%; color: #666; font-weight: normal; margin: 0 14px 14px 14px; font-family: \'Futura Today Light\'; text-align: left; line-height: 120%; }\n</style><div class="oembed-asset oembed-asset-link oembed-asset-usa-today"><a href="http://www.usatoday.com/story/opinion/2016/02/14/scalia-defining-moment-minority-rights-stephen-henderson/80372366/" class="oembed-link-anchor"><div class="oembed-link-thumbnail"><img src="http://www.gannett-cdn.com/-mm-/9065941e142eb769bb76794c742e08d1e14ee558/r=300/http/www.gannett-cdn.com/-mm-/9065941e142eb769bb76794c742e08d1e14ee558/r=300/http/www.gannett-cdn.com/-mm-/d4add04091f6187d02c8ca0c513426288a95d758/c=231-0-895-664/local/-/media/2016/02/14/USATODAY/USATODAY/635910388689035413-salia-pointing.JPG" /></div><p class="oembed-link-title">USA TODAY</p><p class="oembed-link-desc">Scalia&#39;s defining moment: Stephen Henderson</p><div style="clear: both;"></div></a></div></div></div></div><p>This is a pure political power play, as Republicans seek to subvert constitutional governance. The hypocrisy is the tell. As <a href="/story/news/2016/02/13/justice-scalia-found-dead-texas-ranch/80347474/">USA Today reported</a> on Saturday, \xe2\x80\x9cEd Whelan, a former Scalia law clerk and leading conservative on legal issues, argued ... \'Senate Republicans would be <a href="/story/news/2016/02/13/justice-scalia-found-dead-texas-ranch/80347474/">grossly irresponsible</a>\'"\xc2\xa0to confirm an Obama nominee in the final year of his term, adding: "Let the people decide in November who will select the next justice."\xc2\xa0Yet writing in mid-2007 <a href="http://www.nationalreview.com/article/221338/next-supreme-court-vacancy-edward-whelan">for the conservative <em>National Review</em></a>, with 18 months left in\xc2\xa0George W. Bush\'s tenure,\xc2\xa0Whelan urged Bush to nominate another "strong proponent of judicial restraint"\xc2\xa0if he had the opportunity\xc2\xa0and said Senate Democrats\xc2\xa0would pay "severe political costs"\xc2\xa0if they\xc2\xa0blocked a vote.</p><p>A prominent Republican talking point is that Obama has been a divisive president who has caused great disunity in the country. (GOP complaints that Obama has purposefully tried to ruin the United States apparently have nothing to do with the national political discord.) Yet what could be more divisive than a bare-knuckled campaign to impede the president from meeting one of the key obligations of his office?</p><div id="module-position-O4iZ75VNXho" class="story-asset oembed-asset"><div class="story-oembed-wrap "><div \n        class="js-oembed story-oembed story-oembed-usa-today story-oembed-type-link"\n        data-oembed-type="link"\n        data-oembed-provider="usa-today"><style>\n.oembed-asset-link { background: #fff; border-bottom: 1px solid #e1e1e1; }\n.oembed-link-anchor { display: block; clear: both; }\n.oembed-link-thumbnail{ float: left; padding: 14px; }\n.oembed-link-thumbnail img { max-width: 78px; max-height: 60px; display: block; }\np.oembed-link-title { font-size: 75%; color: #009BFF; margin: 0 14px; padding-top: 12px; font-weight:normal; text-align: left; line-height: 120%;  }\np.oembed-link-desc { font-size: 100%; color: #666; font-weight: normal; margin: 0 14px 14px 14px; font-family: \'Futura Today Light\'; text-align: left; line-height: 120%; }\n</style><div class="oembed-asset oembed-asset-link oembed-asset-usa-today"><a href="http://www.usatoday.com/story/opinion/2016/02/13/scalia-death-appreciation-politics-nomination-glenn-reynolds-column/80350008/" class="oembed-link-anchor"><div class="oembed-link-thumbnail"><img src="http://www.gannett-cdn.com/-mm-/9065941e142eb769bb76794c742e08d1e14ee558/r=300/http/www.gannett-cdn.com/-mm-/9065941e142eb769bb76794c742e08d1e14ee558/r=300/http/www.gannett-cdn.com/-mm-/c32182b00ef0a3bb776510d9c42372d65b7e4bea/c=0-207-759-966/local/-/media/2016/02/13/USATODAY/USATODAY/635909822661341976-scalia2.JPG" /></div><p class="oembed-link-title">USA TODAY</p><p class="oembed-link-desc">Antonin Scalia left us wisdom in dissent: Glenn Reynolds</p><div style="clear: both;"></div></a></div></div></div></div><div id="module-position-O4iZ75Vr1cQ" class="story-asset oembed-asset"><div class="story-oembed-wrap "><div \n        class="js-oembed story-oembed story-oembed-usa-today story-oembed-type-link"\n        data-oembed-type="link"\n        data-oembed-provider="usa-today"><style>\n.oembed-asset-link { background: #fff; border-bottom: 1px solid #e1e1e1; }\n.oembed-link-anchor { display: block; clear: both; }\n.oembed-link-thumbnail{ float: left; padding: 14px; }\n.oembed-link-thumbnail img { max-width: 78px; max-height: 60px; display: block; }\np.oembed-link-title { font-size: 75%; color: #009BFF; margin: 0 14px; padding-top: 12px; font-weight:normal; text-align: left; line-height: 120%;  }\np.oembed-link-desc { font-size: 100%; color: #666; font-weight: normal; margin: 0 14px 14px 14px; font-family: \'Futura Today Light\'; text-align: left; line-height: 120%; }\n</style><div class="oembed-asset oembed-asset-link oembed-asset-usa-today"><a href="http://www.usatoday.com/story/opinion/2016/02/13/scalia-text-legacy-clerk-steven-calabresi-column/80349810/" class="oembed-link-anchor"><div class="oembed-link-thumbnail"><img src="http://www.gannett-cdn.com/-mm-/9065941e142eb769bb76794c742e08d1e14ee558/r=300/http/www.gannett-cdn.com/-mm-/9065941e142eb769bb76794c742e08d1e14ee558/r=300/http/www.gannett-cdn.com/-mm-/66b5775364d83e283ad9277a9d08fc59f46cec40/c=121-0-904-783/local/-/media/2016/02/13/USATODAY/USATODAY/635909819440368682-scalia.JPG" /></div><p class="oembed-link-title">USA TODAY</p><p class="oembed-link-desc">Scalia towered over John Marshall: Steven Calabresi</p><div style="clear: both;"></div></a></div></div></div></div><p>Of course, for Republicans looking to score points with voters who think the worst of Obama, this would be good for business. It might also be so \xe2\x80\x94 in political terms \xe2\x80\x94 for the president and the Democrats who seek to succeed him in the White House. An unprecedented GOP effort to thwart Obama on this front would allow Obama to cast the Republicans as outright obstructionists willing to ride roughshod over the Constitution for partisan gain.\xc2\xa0Whomever he might nominate for the post would become a victim of GOP intransigence, and voters who identify or support this nominee would likely not be pleased with Republicans.</p><p>As for Hillary Clinton or Bernie Sanders, what better way to rally the Democratic base than to assail such blatant Republican obstructionism? Every election, candidates in both parties try to rouse voters by noting the Supreme Court could lie in the balance. With this ploy, that task would be far easier. Clinton might also be able to argue that if Democratic voters believe she would have a better shot in November than Sanders, then they ought to support her in the primaries to ensure the GOP doesn\xe2\x80\x99t get away with its attempt to stop a Democratic appointment.</p><p>The GOP move to politicize this Supreme Court vacancy so quickly was foul \xe2\x80\x94 and, unfortunately, a sign that conservatives are committed to making the final months of the Obama presidency as ugly as possible.</p><p><em>David Corn is\xc2\xa0Washington bureau chief for\xc2\xa0</em>Mother Jones<em>\xc2\xa0and an analyst for MSNBC.</em></p><p><em>In addition to its own editorials, USA TODAY publishes diverse opinions from outside writers, including our\xc2\xa0<a href="http://preview.usatoday.com/reporters/boc.html">Board of Contributors.</a>To read more columns like this, go to the\xc2\xa0<a href="http://preview.usatoday.com/opinion/">Opinion front page</a>.</em></p><div id="module-position-O4iZ75VhUpw" class="story-asset inline-share-tools-asset"><div class="inline-share-tools asset-inline-share-tools a